Author::::TerryMcSweeney
DateTime::::2016-02-20T16:51:40Z
So the well-heeled are finding that they are not well-heeled enough. Now they might have some idea what it's like for the rest of us. The awful truth that has to be faced is that in the absence of appropriate legislation, or better still cultural obstacles too great for it to overcome, money gets what money wants. In my part of London, to the horror of most of us, we lost our local brewery because a developer wanted it. No arguments concerning the community value of Young's brewery cut any ice. It made the best beer in the country, in the opinion of many, and its drays, drawn by their beautiful heavy draught horses, were a local feature that we natives were very proud of. Everyone loved the Young's horses. Now they are all gone forever and we are the poorer in those elements of life for which there can be no financial recompense. In place of the brewery we are going to get another faceless concrete tower complete with yet more 'exciting retail opportunities', gated communities and the sort of poncified watering holes that are supposed to substitute for a proper pub. Ask yourselves this: would the Danes allow the Carlsberg brewery in Copenhagen to suffer the same fate, or the Bavarians allow their breweries in Munich to be demolished? Of course they wouldn't. The national culture wouldn't allow it even if the law did. But here we are ruled by Conservative values that do not accept or conceive of any other values but the monetary. We are governed by the collective of arrested development, a gang of public school nerks with, between them, a cumulative emotional age of nine. Hard-faced emotional cripples with a telepathic understanding of what their kindred spirits in the world of finance want them to provide. Provide it they do, and to hell with any other considerations. The UK, or to be more precise the Square Mile, launders quite phenomenal amounts of criminal money that need to be invested somewhere. The UK places no restrictions on foreign ownership of land. Put these two facts together and what happened to Young's brewery and what is happening to Wentworth should not surprise. Richard Caring was born here but inherited his non-dom status from his dad. What government concerned with fairness allows such an obscenity? But this, and all other Conservative administrations, have never been anything but a financiers shag-piece. Our council, Conservative since some disgraceful gerrymandering ensured it would remain so and, incidentally, Maggie's favourite, could have saved Young's but stated loudly that it wanted to be rid of it. The bankers' bum boys saw financial opportunities and all else was swept aside. The sense of loss is awful. Wentforth is likely to experience something similar.



